T1  - Organizational Dysfunctions of Decline
AU  - Cameron, Kim S.
AU  - Whetten, David A.
AU  - Kim, Myung U.
Y1  - 1987/03/01
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255899
DO  - 10.5465/255899
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 126
EP  - 138
VL  - 30
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses the dysfunctional attributes of organizations experiencing periods of decline. Organizations involved in the study were gauged using a number of dysfunctional attributes in organizations identified by scholars, including the centralization of decision making, a lack of long-term planning and a pronounced decrease in the adoption of innovations. According to the author, the aforementioned attributes are characteristic of both stable and declining organizations. Only organizations experiencing growth in revenues seem to avoid these problems.
AB  - The article discusses the dysfunctional attributes of organizations experiencing periods of decline. Organizations involved in the study were gauged using a number of dysfunctional attributes in organizations identified by scholars, including the centralization of decision making, a lack of long-term planning and a pronounced decrease in the adoption of innovations. According to the author, the aforementioned attributes are characteristic of both stable and declining organizations. Only organizations experiencing growth in revenues seem to avoid these problems.
