TY  - JOUR
T1  - Early Intraorganizational Mobility: Patterns and Influences
AU  - Forbes, J. Benjamin
Y1  - 1987/03/01
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255898
DO  - 10.5465/255898
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 110
EP  - 125
VL  - 30
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study examined patterns of early upward mobility for a cohort of 180 employees of an oil company over an 11-year period. The results were not consistent with a strict tournament model of mobility. Later positions were more predictive of career attainment than were early promotions. In addition, initial functional area and the number of different jobs held were related to career attainment. The data supported signaling theory as an explanation of the effects of historical data on decisions about promotions.
AB  - This study examined patterns of early upward mobility for a cohort of 180 employees of an oil company over an 11-year period. The results were not consistent with a strict tournament model of mobility. Later positions were more predictive of career attainment than were early promotions. In addition, initial functional area and the number of different jobs held were related to career attainment. The data supported signaling theory as an explanation of the effects of historical data on decisions about promotions.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255898
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255898
